What is _Thread_local in C11?	<b>Storage-class specifier</b> for thread-local storage duration. Each thread gets its own copy of the variable.<br><pre><code>_Thread_local int tls_errno;</code></pre>
Can _Thread_local combine with other storage classes?	<b>Yes</b>, but only with <b>static</b> or <b>extern</b>. Cannot combine with auto or register.

# === SECTION 3: New Headers ===
What does &lt;stdatomic.h&gt; provide in C11?	<b>Atomic types and operations:</b><br>- atomic_* typedefs (atomic_int, etc.)<br>- memory_order enum<br>- Atomic operation functions<br>- Lock-free property macros
What does &lt;stdalign.h&gt; provide in C11?	<b>Convenience macros:</b><br><pre><code>#define alignas _Alignas
#define alignof _Alignof
#define __alignas_is_defined 1
#define __alignof_is_defined 1</code></pre>
What does &lt;stdnoreturn.h&gt; provide in C11?	<b>Convenience macro:</b><br><pre><code>#define noreturn _Noreturn</code></pre><br>Note: Deprecated in C23 where noreturn becomes a keyword.
What does &lt;threads.h&gt; provide in C11?	<b>Standard threading support:</b><br>- Thread management (thrd_t, thrd_create)<br>- Mutexes (mtx_t)<br>- Condition variables (cnd_t)<br>- Thread-local storage (tss_t)<br>- Once-only execution (call_once)
What does &lt;uchar.h&gt; provide in C11?	<b>Unicode utilities:</b><br>- char16_t and char32_t types<br>- mbrtoc16/c16rtomb (UTF-16 conversion)<br>- mbrtoc32/c32rtomb (UTF-32 conversion)
Is &lt;threads.h&gt; mandatory in C11?	<b>No</b>. Threading support is optional. Check __STDC_NO_THREADS__ to determine availability.

# === SECTION 4: Atomics Deep Dive ===
What is memory_order in C11?	An <b>enum</b> specifying memory ordering constraints for atomic operations.<br><pre><code>enum memory_order {
    memory_order_relaxed,
    memory_order_consume,
    memory_order_acquire,
    memory_order_release,
    memory_order_acq_rel,
    memory_order_seq_cst
};</code></pre>
What does memory_order_relaxed provide?	<b>No synchronization or ordering</b>. Only atomicity is guaranteed. Fastest but provides no happens-before relationships.
What does memory_order_acquire provide?	<b>Acquire semantics</b>. No reads/writes in the current thread can be reordered before this load. Pairs with release operations.
What does memory_order_release provide?	<b>Release semantics</b>. No reads/writes in the current thread can be reordered after this store. Pairs with acquire operations.
What does memory_order_acq_rel provide?	<b>Both acquire and release</b>. Used for read-modify-write operations that need full synchronization in both directions.
What does memory_order_seq_cst provide?	<b>Sequential consistency</b>. Strongest ordering. All seq_cst operations form a single total order visible to all threads. Default for non-explicit operations.
What does atomic_store do?	<b>Atomically stores</b> a value. Uses memory_order_seq_cst by default.<br><pre><code>atomic_int x;
atomic_store(&amp;x, 42);
// explicit: atomic_store_explicit(&amp;x, 42, memory_order_release);</code></pre>
What does atomic_load do?	<b>Atomically loads</b> a value. Uses memory_order_seq_cst by default.<br><pre><code>atomic_int x = 42;
int val = atomic_load(&amp;x);
// explicit: atomic_load_explicit(&amp;x, memory_order_acquire);</code></pre>
What does atomic_exchange do?	<b>Atomically replaces</b> the value and returns the old value (read-modify-write).<br><pre><code>atomic_int x = 1;
int old = atomic_exchange(&amp;x, 2);
// old == 1, x == 2</code></pre>
What does atomic_fetch_add do?	<b>Atomically adds</b> to the value and returns the <b>old</b> value.<br><pre><code>atomic_int counter = 0;
int prev = atomic_fetch_add(&amp;counter, 1);
// prev == 0, counter == 1</code></pre>
What does atomic_fetch_sub do?	<b>Atomically subtracts</b> from the value and returns the <b>old</b> value.<br><pre><code>atomic_int counter = 5;
int prev = atomic_fetch_sub(&amp;counter, 1);
// prev == 5, counter == 4</code></pre>
What is the difference between atomic_compare_exchange_strong and _weak?	<b>Strong:</b> Only fails if comparison fails.<br><b>Weak:</b> May spuriously fail even if comparison succeeds (but faster on some platforms).<br><br>Use weak in loops, strong for single attempts.
Give the signature of atomic_compare_exchange_strong.	<pre><code>_Bool atomic_compare_exchange_strong(
    volatile A *object,
    C *expected,
    C desired
);</code></pre><br>If *object == *expected, stores desired and returns true. Otherwise updates expected with current value and returns false.
What is atomic_flag in C11?	The <b>only guaranteed lock-free</b> atomic type. A boolean flag for spinlocks.<br><pre><code>atomic_flag lock = ATOMIC_FLAG_INIT;</code></pre>
What does atomic_flag_test_and_set do?	<b>Atomically sets</b> the flag to true and returns the <b>previous</b> value.<br><pre><code>while (atomic_flag_test_and_set(&amp;lock)) {
    // spin
}
// critical section
atomic_flag_clear(&amp;lock);</code></pre>
What does atomic_flag_clear do?	<b>Atomically sets</b> the flag to false.<br><pre><code>atomic_flag_clear(&amp;lock);
// explicit: atomic_flag_clear_explicit(&amp;lock, memory_order_release);</code></pre>
What do ATOMIC_*_LOCK_FREE macros indicate?	Whether atomic operations on a type are <b>lock-free</b>.<br>Values: 0 (never), 1 (sometimes), 2 (always).<br><pre><code>ATOMIC_INT_LOCK_FREE
ATOMIC_POINTER_LOCK_FREE
ATOMIC_LLONG_LOCK_FREE</code></pre>
What does atomic_init do?	<b>Initializes</b> an atomic object. <b>Not atomic</b> - concurrent access during init is a data race.<br><pre><code>atomic_int x;
atomic_init(&amp;x, 0);</code></pre>
What does atomic_is_lock_free do?	Returns whether operations on a <b>specific atomic object</b> are lock-free (runtime check).<br><pre><code>atomic_int x;
if (atomic_is_lock_free(&amp;x)) { ... }</code></pre>

# === SECTION 5: Threading ===
What is thrd_t in C11?	An <b>implementation-defined type</b> identifying a thread. Similar to pthread_t.<br><pre><code>thrd_t thread;</code></pre>
What is the signature of thrd_create?	<pre><code>int thrd_create(
    thrd_t *thr,
    thrd_start_t func,
    void *arg
);</code></pre><br>thrd_start_t is int (*)(void*).
What does thrd_join do?	<b>Blocks</b> until the specified thread terminates. Optionally retrieves the return value.<br><pre><code>int result;
thrd_join(thread, &amp;result);</code></pre>
What does thrd_detach do?	<b>Detaches</b> a thread. Resources are automatically released when it exits. Cannot be joined afterward.<br><pre><code>thrd_detach(thread);</code></pre>
What does thrd_current return?	The <b>thrd_t</b> identifier of the calling thread.<br><pre><code>thrd_t me = thrd_current();</code></pre>
What does thrd_equal do?	<b>Compares</b> two thrd_t identifiers. Returns non-zero if they refer to the same thread.<br><pre><code>if (thrd_equal(t1, t2)) { ... }</code></pre>
What does thrd_sleep do?	<b>Suspends</b> the calling thread for at least the specified duration.<br><pre><code>struct timespec ts = {.tv_sec = 1, .tv_nsec = 0};
thrd_sleep(&amp;ts, NULL);</code></pre>
What does thrd_yield do?	<b>Yields</b> execution, allowing other threads to run. Advisory only.<br><pre><code>thrd_yield();</code></pre>
What does thrd_exit do?	<b>Terminates</b> the calling thread with the specified result code.<br><pre><code>thrd_exit(0);</code></pre>
What is mtx_t in C11?	<b>Mutex type</b> for mutual exclusion.<br><pre><code>mtx_t mutex;</code></pre>
What are the mtx_init type flags?	<pre><code>mtx_plain     // basic mutex
mtx_timed     // supports timed locking
mtx_recursive // can be locked multiple times by same thread
// can combine: mtx_timed | mtx_recursive</code></pre>
What does mtx_lock do?	<b>Blocks</b> until the mutex is acquired.<br><pre><code>mtx_lock(&amp;mutex);
// critical section
mtx_unlock(&amp;mutex);</code></pre>
What does mtx_trylock do?	<b>Attempts</b> to acquire mutex without blocking. Returns thrd_success or thrd_busy.<br><pre><code>if (mtx_trylock(&amp;mutex) == thrd_success) { ... }</code></pre>
What does mtx_timedlock do?	<b>Attempts</b> to acquire mutex with timeout. Returns thrd_success or thrd_timedout.<br><pre><code>struct timespec deadline;
mtx_timedlock(&amp;mutex, &amp;deadline);</code></pre>
What is cnd_t in C11?	<b>Condition variable type</b> for thread synchronization.<br><pre><code>cnd_t cond;</code></pre>
What does cnd_wait do?	<b>Atomically unlocks</b> the mutex and blocks until signaled, then re-locks.<br><pre><code>mtx_lock(&amp;mutex);
while (!condition)
    cnd_wait(&amp;cond, &amp;mutex);
mtx_unlock(&amp;mutex);</code></pre>
What does cnd_signal do?	<b>Unblocks</b> at least one thread waiting on the condition variable.<br><pre><code>cnd_signal(&amp;cond);</code></pre>
What does cnd_broadcast do?	<b>Unblocks all</b> threads waiting on the condition variable.<br><pre><code>cnd_broadcast(&amp;cond);</code></pre>
What is once_flag and call_once for?	<b>One-time initialization</b>. The function is called exactly once regardless of how many threads call call_once.<br><pre><code>once_flag flag = ONCE_FLAG_INIT;
call_once(&amp;flag, init_function);</code></pre>
What is tss_t in C11?	<b>Thread-specific storage</b> key type. Each thread can store a unique value associated with the key.<br><pre><code>tss_t key;
tss_create(&amp;key, destructor_func);</code></pre>
What are the C11 thread function return codes?	<pre><code>thrd_success  // operation succeeded
thrd_nomem    // memory allocation failed
thrd_timedout // timed operation timed out
thrd_busy     // resource busy (trylock failed)
thrd_error    // other error occurred</code></pre>

# === SECTION 6: Unicode Support ===
What is char16_t in C11?	An <b>unsigned integer type</b> for 16-bit characters (UTF-16 code units). Defined in &lt;uchar.h&gt;.<br><pre><code>char16_t ch = u'A';</code></pre>
What is char32_t in C11?	An <b>unsigned integer type</b> for 32-bit characters (UTF-32 code points). Defined in &lt;uchar.h&gt;.<br><pre><code>char32_t ch = U'\U0001F600';</code></pre>
What does the u8 string literal prefix produce?	A <b>UTF-8 encoded</b> string (char array).<br><pre><code>const char *s = u8"Hello";</code></pre>
What does the u string literal prefix produce?	A <b>UTF-16 encoded</b> string (char16_t array).<br><pre><code>const char16_t *s = u"Hello";</code></pre>
What does the U string literal prefix produce?	A <b>UTF-32 encoded</b> string (char32_t array).<br><pre><code>const char32_t *s = U"Hello \U0001F600";</code></pre>
What does mbrtoc16 do?	Converts a <b>multibyte character to UTF-16</b>. May produce one or two char16_t (surrogate pair).<br><pre><code>size_t mbrtoc16(char16_t *pc16, const char *s,
                size_t n, mbstate_t *ps);</code></pre>
What does c16rtomb do?	Converts a <b>UTF-16 character to multibyte</b>.<br><pre><code>size_t c16rtomb(char *s, char16_t c16,
                mbstate_t *ps);</code></pre>
What does mbrtoc32 do?	Converts a <b>multibyte character to UTF-32</b>.<br><pre><code>size_t mbrtoc32(char32_t *pc32, const char *s,
                size_t n, mbstate_t *ps);</code></pre>

# === SECTION 7: Library Additions ===
What is aligned_alloc in C11?	Allocates memory with specified <b>alignment</b>.<br><pre><code>void *aligned_alloc(size_t alignment, size_t size);</code></pre><br>size must be a multiple of alignment. Free with free().
What is the key constraint on aligned_alloc?	The <b>size must be an integral multiple of alignment</b>. Otherwise behavior is undefined.
What is quick_exit in C11?	<b>Fast program termination</b>. Calls at_quick_exit handlers then _Exit. Does NOT call atexit handlers.<br><pre><code>quick_exit(EXIT_SUCCESS);</code></pre>
What is at_quick_exit in C11?	Registers a function to be called by <b>quick_exit</b> (in reverse order of registration).<br><pre><code>at_quick_exit(cleanup_func);</code></pre>
What is the difference between quick_exit and exit?	<b>exit:</b> Calls atexit handlers, flushes streams, closes files.<br><b>quick_exit:</b> Only calls at_quick_exit handlers, then _Exit (no cleanup).
What is struct timespec in C11?	A structure for <b>time with nanosecond precision</b>.<br><pre><code>struct timespec {
    time_t tv_sec;  // seconds
    long tv_nsec;   // nanoseconds [0, 999999999]
};</code></pre>
What is timespec_get in C11?	Fills a timespec with the <b>current time</b>.<br><pre><code>struct timespec ts;
timespec_get(&amp;ts, TIME_UTC);</code></pre>
What is TIME_UTC in C11?	A macro used with timespec_get to request <b>calendar time</b> in UTC. The epoch is implementation-defined.
What does the "x" fopen mode do in C11?	<b>Exclusive create</b>. Fails if the file already exists. Prevents accidental overwriting.<br><pre><code>FILE *f = fopen("lockfile", "wx");
if (!f) { /* file exists or error */ }</code></pre>
Why was gets removed in C11?	<b>Buffer overflow vulnerability</b>. gets() had no way to limit input length. Replaced by fgets() or gets_s().
What replaces gets() in C11?	<b>fgets()</b> (standard) or <b>gets_s()</b> (Annex K).<br><pre><code>char buf[100];
fgets(buf, sizeof buf, stdin);</code></pre>

# === SECTION 8: Annex K Bounds-Checking ===
What is __STDC_WANT_LIB_EXT1__ for?	<b>Request Annex K functions</b>. Define as 1 before including headers to get _s function declarations.<br><pre><code>#define __STDC_WANT_LIB_EXT1__ 1
#include &lt;string.h&gt;</code></pre>
What is constraint_handler_t?	The <b>type of Annex K error handlers</b>.<br><pre><code>typedef void (*constraint_handler_t)(
    const char *msg,
    void *ptr,
    errno_t error
);</code></pre>
What does set_constraint_handler_s do?	<b>Sets the runtime-constraint handler</b> for Annex K functions. Returns the previous handler.<br><pre><code>set_constraint_handler_s(my_handler);</code></pre>
What is abort_handler_s?	The <b>default Annex K handler</b>. Writes a message to stderr and calls abort().
What is ignore_handler_s?	An Annex K handler that <b>does nothing</b>. Functions return error codes but don't abort.
What is strcpy_s?	<b>Bounds-checked string copy</b>.<br><pre><code>errno_t strcpy_s(char *dest, rsize_t destsz,
                 const char *src);</code></pre>
What is sprintf_s?	<b>Bounds-checked sprintf</b>.<br><pre><code>int sprintf_s(char *s, rsize_t n,
              const char *format, ...);</code></pre>
What is rsize_t in Annex K?	A size_t-like type with a <b>maximum value</b> (RSIZE_MAX). Values exceeding RSIZE_MAX trigger constraint handlers.
What is RSIZE_MAX?	The <b>maximum valid value</b> for rsize_t parameters. Typically SIZE_MAX &gt;&gt; 1. Prevents suspiciously large size values.

# === SECTION 9: Language Features ===
What are anonymous structs/unions in C11?	Unnamed struct/union members whose fields are accessed as if they belong to the enclosing struct.<br><pre><code>struct vec3 {
    union {
        struct { float x, y, z; };
        float v[3];
    };
};
vec3 v; v.x = 1.0f; // direct access</code></pre>
What is the benefit of anonymous structs/unions?	<b>Cleaner syntax</b>. No need to name intermediate containers. Common in hardware registers and variant types.
What are CMPLX, CMPLXF, CMPLXL macros?	<b>Complex number construction</b> in &lt;complex.h&gt;. Properly preserve signed zeros.<br><pre><code>double complex z = CMPLX(0.0, -0.0);</code></pre>
Why use CMPLX instead of arithmetic construction?	<b>Preserves signed zeros</b>. (0.0 + -0.0*I) may not preserve -0.0 in the imaginary part due to arithmetic rules.
Are VLAs mandatory in C11?	<b>No</b>. Variable Length Arrays became optional. Check __STDC_NO_VLA__ for availability.
What changed about complex numbers in C11?	They became <b>optional</b>. Check __STDC_NO_COMPLEX__. They were mandatory in C99.
"}

