{"file_path": "c89-flashcards.tsv", "contents": "# C89 (ANSI C / X3.159-1989) Flashcard Deck
# Import: Anki > File > Import, select TSV, Fields separated by Tab
# Enable "Allow HTML in fields"
# The foundational C standard - covers complete language specification

# === SECTION 1: Keywords (32 total) ===
List all 32 C89 keywords.	<pre><code>auto     break    case     char
const    continue default  do
double   else     enum     extern
float    for      goto     if
int      long     register return
short    signed   sizeof   static
struct   switch   typedef  union
unsigned void     volatile while</code></pre>
What does the auto keyword do in C89?	<b>Storage class specifier</b> for automatic (local) storage duration. Default for local variables, rarely written explicitly.<br><pre><code>auto int x = 5; // same as: int x = 5;</code></pre>
What does the register keyword do in C89?	<b>Hint to compiler</b> to store variable in a CPU register for fast access. Cannot take address of register variables.<br><pre><code>register int i;
for (i = 0; i &lt; 1000; i++) { ... }</code></pre>
What does the static keyword do in C89?	<b>Two uses:</b><br>1. Local variable: persists across function calls<br>2. File scope: limits visibility to current translation unit<br><pre><code>static int counter = 0;  // persistent local
static void helper(void); // internal linkage</code></pre>
What does the extern keyword do in C89?	<b>Declares</b> a variable or function defined elsewhere (external linkage).<br><pre><code>extern int global_count;  // defined in another file
extern void func(void);   // optional for functions</code></pre>
What does the const keyword do in C89?	<b>Type qualifier</b> indicating the value cannot be modified after initialization.<br><pre><code>const int MAX = 100;
const char *str = "hello"; // pointer to const char</code></pre>
What does the volatile keyword do in C89?	<b>Type qualifier</b> telling compiler the value may change unexpectedly (hardware registers, signal handlers). Prevents optimization.<br><pre><code>volatile int *port = (int *)0x40000000;</code></pre>
What does typedef do in C89?	<b>Creates an alias</b> for a type. Does not create a new type.<br><pre><code>typedef unsigned long size_t;
typedef struct node Node;</code></pre>
What does sizeof do in C89?	<b>Operator</b> returning the size in bytes of a type or expression (as size_t).<br><pre><code>sizeof(int)       // size of int
sizeof(array)     // total array size
sizeof array[0]   // size of one element</code></pre>

# === SECTION 2: Data Types ===
What are the basic integer types in C89?	<pre><code>char              // at least 8 bits
short [int]       // at least 16 bits
int               // at least 16 bits
long [int]        // at least 32 bits</code></pre><br>Each can be signed or unsigned.
What are the floating-point types in C89?	<pre><code>float       // single precision
double      // double precision
long double // extended precision</code></pre>
What is the void type in C89?	<b>Incomplete type</b> with no values.<br>Uses:<br>- Function returning nothing: void func(void)<br>- Generic pointer: void *ptr<br>- Discard expression: (void)unused_result;
What does signed vs unsigned mean?	<b>signed:</b> Can represent negative values (two's complement typical)<br><b>unsigned:</b> Only non-negative values, larger positive range<br><pre><code>signed char:   -128 to 127
unsigned char: 0 to 255</code></pre>
What is the minimum range of int in C89?	<b>-32767 to +32767</b> (at least 16 bits). Defined in &lt;limits.h&gt; as INT_MIN and INT_MAX.
What is the minimum range of long in C89?	<b>-2147483647 to +2147483647</b> (at least 32 bits). Defined in &lt;limits.h&gt; as LONG_MIN and LONG_MAX.
What is the char type in C89?	<b>Smallest addressable unit</b>. May be signed or unsigned (implementation-defined). Always exactly 1 byte by definition.
What header defines integer limits in C89?	<b>&lt;limits.h&gt;</b><br><pre><code>CHAR_BIT   // bits in char (at least 8)
CHAR_MIN, CHAR_MAX
INT_MIN, INT_MAX
LONG_MIN, LONG_MAX
UCHAR_MAX, UINT_MAX, ULONG_MAX</code></pre>
What header defines floating-point limits in C89?	<b>&lt;float.h&gt;</b><br><pre><code>FLT_MIN, FLT_MAX, FLT_EPSILON
DBL_MIN, DBL_MAX, DBL_EPSILON
LDBL_MIN, LDBL_MAX</code></pre>

# === SECTION 3: Operators ===
List the arithmetic operators in C89.	<pre><code>+   // addition, unary plus
-   // subtraction, unary minus
*   // multiplication
/   // division
%   // modulo (integers only)</code></pre>
List the relational operators in C89.	<pre><code>&lt;   // less than
&gt;   // greater than
&lt;=  // less than or equal
&gt;=  // greater than or equal
==  // equal
!=  // not equal</code></pre><br>Result is int: 0 (false) or 1 (true).
List the logical operators in C89.	<pre><code>&amp;&amp;  // logical AND (short-circuit)
||  // logical OR (short-circuit)
!   // logical NOT</code></pre><br>Operands treated as boolean (0 = false, non-zero = true).
List the bitwise operators in C89.	<pre><code>&amp;   // bitwise AND
|   // bitwise OR
^   // bitwise XOR
~   // bitwise NOT (ones complement)
&lt;&lt;  // left shift
&gt;&gt;  // right shift</code></pre>
List the assignment operators in C89.	<pre><code>=   // simple assignment
+=  -= *= /= %=   // compound arithmetic
&amp;=  |= ^=         // compound bitwise
&lt;&lt;= &gt;&gt;=           // compound shift</code></pre>
What are the increment/decrement operators?	<pre><code>++x  // pre-increment: increment, return new value
x++  // post-increment: return old value, increment
--x  // pre-decrement
x--  // post-decrement</code></pre>
What is the conditional (ternary) operator?	<pre><code>condition ? expr1 : expr2</code></pre><br>If condition is true, evaluates and returns expr1; otherwise expr2.
What is the comma operator?	Evaluates left operand, discards result, evaluates and returns right operand.<br><pre><code>x = (a++, b++, c);  // x = c</code></pre>
What is the sizeof operator?	Returns size in bytes as size_t. Can take type or expression.<br><pre><code>sizeof(int)
sizeof x
sizeof(struct foo)</code></pre>
What are the pointer operators in C89?	<pre><code>&amp;   // address-of: get pointer to object
*   // dereference: access pointed-to object
-&gt;  // member access through pointer
[]  // array subscript (pointer + offset)</code></pre>
What is C89 operator precedence (highest to lowest)?	<pre><code>() [] -&gt; .              // postfix
! ~ ++ -- + - * &amp; sizeof // unary (right-to-left)
* / %                    // multiplicative
+ -                      // additive
&lt;&lt; &gt;&gt;                   // shift
&lt; &lt;= &gt; &gt;=               // relational
== !=                    // equality
&amp;                        // bitwise AND
^                        // bitwise XOR
|                        // bitwise OR
&amp;&amp;                       // logical AND
||                       // logical OR
?:                       // conditional (R-to-L)
= += -= etc.             // assignment (R-to-L)
,                        // comma</code></pre>

# === SECTION 4: Control Flow ===
What is the if statement syntax?	<pre><code>if (condition) {
    // executed if condition != 0
} else if (other_condition) {
    // optional
} else {
    // optional
}</code></pre>
What is the switch statement syntax?	<pre><code>switch (integer_expression) {
    case const1:
        statements;
        break;
    case const2:
    case const3:  // fall-through
        statements;
        break;
    default:
        statements;
}</code></pre>
What is the for loop syntax?	<pre><code>for (init; condition; update) {
    body;
}</code></pre><br>All three expressions are optional. Infinite loop: for (;;)
What is the while loop syntax?	<pre><code>while (condition) {
    body;  // may execute 0 times
}</code></pre>
What is the do-while loop syntax?	<pre><code>do {
    body;  // executes at least once
} while (condition);</code></pre><br>Note the semicolon after the condition.
What does break do?	<b>Exits</b> the innermost enclosing loop or switch statement immediately.
What does continue do?	<b>Skips</b> remaining body of innermost loop and proceeds to next iteration (re-evaluates condition).
What does goto do?	<b>Unconditional jump</b> to a labeled statement within the same function.<br><pre><code>goto cleanup;
...
cleanup:
    free(ptr);</code></pre>
What does return do?	<b>Exits</b> the current function, optionally returning a value.<br><pre><code>return;      // void function
return 0;    // returns value</code></pre>

# === SECTION 5: Functions ===
What is a function prototype in C89?	A <b>declaration</b> specifying return type and parameter types, without the body.<br><pre><code>int add(int a, int b);
void process(char *str);</code></pre>
What is the old-style (K&R) function definition?	Pre-ANSI style with types declared separately (still valid in C89).<br><pre><code>int add(a, b)
int a;
int b;
{
    return a + b;
}</code></pre>
What is the ANSI-style function definition?	Modern prototype form with parameters in the declaration.<br><pre><code>int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}</code></pre>
How do you declare a function taking no parameters in C89?	Use <b>void</b> in the parameter list.<br><pre><code>int get_count(void);</code></pre><br>Empty parentheses () means unspecified parameters (old style).
What is the difference between () and (void) in declarations?	<b>(void):</b> Function takes no arguments<br><b>():</b> Unspecified parameters (old-style, accepts any arguments)<br><pre><code>int f(void);  // no arguments
int g();      // unknown arguments (avoid)</code></pre>
What is a variadic function in C89?	A function accepting a <b>variable number of arguments</b>. Uses &lt;stdarg.h&gt;.<br><pre><code>int printf(const char *fmt, ...);</code></pre>
What macros does &lt;stdarg.h&gt; provide?	<pre><code>va_list   // type for argument list
va_start  // initialize va_list
va_arg    // get next argument
va_end    // clean up</code></pre>
Give an example of using stdarg.h.	<pre><code>#include &lt;stdarg.h&gt;
int sum(int count, ...) {
    va_list ap;
    va_start(ap, count);
    int total = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; count; i++)
        total += va_arg(ap, int);
    va_end(ap);
    return total;
}</code></pre>

# === SECTION 6: Pointers ===
What is a pointer in C89?	A variable that <b>holds a memory address</b>. Declared with *.<br><pre><code>int x = 10;
int *p = &amp;x;  // p points to x
*p = 20;      // x is now 20</code></pre>
What is the NULL pointer?	A pointer value indicating <b>no valid address</b>. Defined in &lt;stddef.h&gt;, &lt;stdlib.h&gt;, etc.<br><pre><code>int *p = NULL;
if (p != NULL) { ... }</code></pre>
What is pointer arithmetic?	Adding/subtracting integers to/from pointers. Moves by <b>element size</b>.<br><pre><code>int arr[5];
int *p = arr;
p++;        // moves sizeof(int) bytes
p += 2;     // moves 2*sizeof(int) bytes</code></pre>
What is the relationship between arrays and pointers?	Array name <b>decays to pointer</b> to first element in most contexts.<br><pre><code>int arr[5];
int *p = arr;     // p = &amp;arr[0]
arr[i] == *(p+i)  // equivalent access</code></pre>
What is a pointer to pointer?	A pointer that holds the <b>address of another pointer</b>.<br><pre><code>int x = 10;
int *p = &amp;x;
int **pp = &amp;p;
**pp = 20;  // x is now 20</code></pre>
What is a function pointer?	A pointer to a <b>function's code</b>.<br><pre><code>int (*fp)(int, int);  // pointer to int(int,int)
fp = add;
int result = fp(3, 4);</code></pre>
What is a void pointer?	A <b>generic pointer</b> that can point to any type. Cannot be dereferenced without casting.<br><pre><code>void *p = malloc(100);
int *ip = (int *)p;</code></pre>

# === SECTION 7: Arrays ===
How do you declare an array in C89?	<pre><code>int arr[10];           // 10 ints
char str[100];         // 100 chars
double matrix[3][4];   // 3x4 matrix</code></pre><br>Size must be a constant expression.
How do you initialize an array in C89?	<pre><code>int arr[5] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
int arr[] = {1, 2, 3};  // size inferred (3)
int arr[5] = {1, 2};    // rest are 0
int arr[5] = {0};       // all zeros</code></pre>
What is array-to-pointer decay?	Arrays automatically convert to pointers to their first element, except with sizeof or &amp;.<br><pre><code>int arr[5];
int *p = arr;        // decay: p = &amp;arr[0]
sizeof(arr);         // no decay: returns 20
&amp;arr;                // no decay: int(*)[5]</code></pre>
What is a multidimensional array?	An <b>array of arrays</b>. Stored in row-major order.<br><pre><code>int matrix[3][4];      // 3 rows, 4 columns
matrix[1][2] = 5;      // row 1, column 2
// equivalent: *(*(matrix+1)+2) = 5</code></pre>
How do you pass an array to a function?	Arrays decay to pointers. Size is lost.<br><pre><code>void f(int arr[], int size);  // equivalent to:
void f(int *arr, int size);

// For 2D arrays, specify all but first dimension:
void g(int arr[][4], int rows);</code></pre>

# === SECTION 8: Structures and Unions ===
What is a struct in C89?	A <b>composite type</b> grouping related variables.<br><pre><code>struct point {
    int x;
    int y;
};
struct point p = {10, 20};
p.x = 30;</code></pre>
What is a union in C89?	A type where all members <b>share the same memory</b>. Only one member is valid at a time.<br><pre><code>union value {
    int i;
    float f;
    char c;
};
sizeof(union value) == sizeof(largest member)</code></pre>
How do you access struct members?	<pre><code>struct point p;
p.x = 10;       // direct access with .

struct point *pp = &amp;p;
pp-&gt;x = 20;     // pointer access with -&gt;
(*pp).x = 20;   // equivalent</code></pre>
What is struct padding?	Compilers add <b>padding bytes</b> for alignment. Members may not be contiguous.<br><pre><code>struct s {
    char c;     // 1 byte + 3 padding
    int i;      // 4 bytes
};  // sizeof = 8, not 5</code></pre>
What is a bit-field in C89?	Struct members with <b>specified bit widths</b>.<br><pre><code>struct flags {
    unsigned int ready : 1;
    unsigned int error : 1;
    unsigned int count : 6;
};</code></pre>
Can you have a pointer to a struct inside the struct?	<b>Yes</b>. Self-referential structures enable linked data structures.<br><pre><code>struct node {
    int data;
    struct node *next;
};</code></pre>

# === SECTION 9: Enumerations ===
What is an enum in C89?	A set of <b>named integer constants</b>.<br><pre><code>enum color { RED, GREEN, BLUE };
// RED=0, GREEN=1, BLUE=2

enum color c = GREEN;</code></pre>
How do you specify enum values?	<pre><code>enum status {
    OK = 0,
    ERROR = -1,
    PENDING = 100,
    DONE       // 101 (continues from previous)
};</code></pre>
What type is an enum value?	<b>int</b>. Enums are compatible with int and can be used interchangeably.

# === SECTION 10: Preprocessor ===
What are the preprocessor directives in C89?	<pre><code>#include   // include file
#define    // define macro
#undef     // undefine macro
#if #ifdef #ifndef #elif #else #endif // conditional
#line      // set line number
#error     // generate error
#pragma    // implementation-defined</code></pre>
How does #include work?	<pre><code>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;   // search system paths
#include "myfile.h"  // search current dir first</code></pre><br>Textually inserts the file contents.
How does #define work for constants?	<pre><code>#define MAX 100
#define PI 3.14159
#define MSG "Hello"</code></pre><br>Simple text substitution.
How does #define work for macros?	<pre><code>#define MAX(a,b) ((a) &gt; (b) ? (a) : (b))
#define SQUARE(x) ((x) * (x))</code></pre><br>Parenthesize everything to avoid precedence bugs.
What is the # (stringizing) operator?	Converts macro argument to <b>string literal</b>.<br><pre><code>#define STR(x) #x
STR(hello)  // "hello"</code></pre>
What is the ## (token pasting) operator?	<b>Concatenates</b> two tokens.<br><pre><code>#define CONCAT(a,b) a##b
CONCAT(foo,bar)  // foobar</code></pre>
What are the predefined macros in C89?	<pre><code>__LINE__  // current line number
__FILE__  // current filename
__DATE__  // compilation date "Mmm dd yyyy"
__TIME__  // compilation time "hh:mm:ss"
__STDC__  // 1 if conforming implementation</code></pre>
What does #ifdef do?	<b>Conditional compilation</b>. Block included if macro is defined.<br><pre><code>#ifdef DEBUG
    printf("debug: x=%d\n", x);
#endif</code></pre>
What does #ifndef do?	<b>Conditional compilation</b>. Block included if macro is NOT defined. Common for include guards.<br><pre><code>#ifndef HEADER_H
#define HEADER_H
// header contents
#endif</code></pre>

# === SECTION 11: Standard Library Headers ===
List the C89 standard library headers.	<pre><code>&lt;assert.h&gt;  &lt;ctype.h&gt;   &lt;errno.h&gt;
&lt;float.h&gt;   &lt;limits.h&gt;  &lt;locale.h&gt;
&lt;math.h&gt;    &lt;setjmp.h&gt;  &lt;signal.h&gt;
&lt;stdarg.h&gt;  &lt;stddef.h&gt;  &lt;stdio.h&gt;
&lt;stdlib.h&gt;  &lt;string.h&gt;  &lt;time.h&gt;</code></pre><br>15 standard headers.
What does &lt;stdio.h&gt; provide?	<b>Input/Output:</b><br><pre><code>FILE, stdin, stdout, stderr
printf, scanf, fprintf, fscanf
fopen, fclose, fread, fwrite
fgets, fputs, getc, putc
fseek, ftell, rewind</code></pre>
What does &lt;stdlib.h&gt; provide?	<b>General utilities:</b><br><pre><code>malloc, calloc, realloc, free
atoi, atof, atol, strtol, strtod
rand, srand
qsort, bsearch
exit, abort, atexit
abs, labs, div, ldiv</code></pre>
What does &lt;string.h&gt; provide?	<b>String/memory functions:</b><br><pre><code>strlen, strcpy, strncpy, strcat, strncat
strcmp, strncmp, strchr, strrchr, strstr
memcpy, memmove, memset, memcmp, memchr</code></pre>
What does &lt;math.h&gt; provide?	<b>Math functions:</b><br><pre><code>sin, cos, tan, asin, acos, atan, atan2
sinh, cosh, tanh
exp, log, log10, pow, sqrt
ceil, floor, fabs, fmod</code></pre>
What does &lt;ctype.h&gt; provide?	<b>Character classification:</b><br><pre><code>isalpha, isdigit, isalnum, isspace
isupper, islower, isprint, ispunct
toupper, tolower</code></pre>
What does &lt;assert.h&gt; provide?	<b>assert macro</b> for runtime checks. If expression is false, prints message and aborts.<br><pre><code>assert(ptr != NULL);
// disabled if NDEBUG defined</code></pre>
What does &lt;errno.h&gt; provide?	<b>errno</b> macro and error codes.<br><pre><code>errno = 0;
result = sqrt(-1);
if (errno == EDOM) { ... }</code></pre>
What does &lt;setjmp.h&gt; provide?	<b>Non-local jumps</b> for error handling.<br><pre><code>jmp_buf env;
if (setjmp(env) == 0) {
    // normal execution
} else {
    // returned from longjmp
}
longjmp(env, 1);  // jump back</code></pre>
What does &lt;signal.h&gt; provide?	<b>Signal handling:</b><br><pre><code>signal(SIGINT, handler);
raise(SIGTERM);</code></pre><br>Standard signals: SIGABRT, SIGFPE, SIGILL, SIGINT, SIGSEGV, SIGTERM
What does &lt;time.h&gt; provide?	<b>Date and time:</b><br><pre><code>time_t, struct tm, clock_t
time, difftime, mktime
gmtime, localtime, strftime
clock</code></pre>
What does &lt;stddef.h&gt; provide?	<b>Common definitions:</b><br><pre><code>NULL      // null pointer constant
size_t    // unsigned size type
ptrdiff_t // signed pointer difference type
offsetof  // byte offset of struct member</code></pre>

# === SECTION 12: Memory Management ===
What does malloc do?	<b>Allocates</b> uninitialized memory. Returns NULL on failure.<br><pre><code>int *p = malloc(10 * sizeof(int));
if (p == NULL) { /* error */ }</code></pre>
What does calloc do?	<b>Allocates and zero-initializes</b> memory.<br><pre><code>int *p = calloc(10, sizeof(int));
// all 10 ints are initialized to 0</code></pre>
What does realloc do?	<b>Resizes</b> previously allocated memory. May move the block.<br><pre><code>p = realloc(p, 20 * sizeof(int));
// preserve original if realloc fails:
int *tmp = realloc(p, newsize);
if (tmp) p = tmp;</code></pre>
What does free do?	<b>Deallocates</b> memory from malloc/calloc/realloc. Passing NULL is safe (no-op).<br><pre><code>free(p);
p = NULL;  // good practice</code></pre>
What is a memory leak?	Allocated memory that is <b>no longer reachable</b> and cannot be freed. Wastes memory over time.
What is a dangling pointer?	A pointer to memory that has been <b>freed or is out of scope</b>. Dereferencing is undefined behavior.
What is a double free?	Calling free() on the <b>same pointer twice</b>. Undefined behavior, often causes crashes or security vulnerabilities.

# === SECTION 13: I/O Details ===
What is the difference between text and binary mode?	<b>Text mode:</b> Newline translation (\\n to platform-specific). Character-oriented.<br><b>Binary mode:</b> No translation. Byte-for-byte exact.
What are the fopen mode strings?	<pre><code>"r"  // read text
"w"  // write text (truncate/create)
"a"  // append text
"r+" // read+write text
"w+" // read+write (truncate/create)
"a+" // read+append
"rb" "wb" "ab" // binary modes</code></pre>
What does printf return?	The <b>number of characters printed</b>, or negative on error.<br><pre><code>int n = printf("Hello");  // n = 5</code></pre>
What are the printf format specifiers?	<pre><code>%d %i  // int (decimal)
%u     // unsigned int
%x %X  // unsigned hex
%o     // unsigned octal
%f %F  // double
%e %E  // scientific notation
%g %G  // shortest of %f or %e
%c     // char
%s     // string
%p     // pointer
%%     // literal %</code></pre>
What does scanf return?	The <b>number of items successfully converted</b>, or EOF on error/end.<br><pre><code>int n;
if (scanf("%d", &amp;n) != 1) { /* error */ }</code></pre>
What is the difference between getc and fgetc?	<b>getc:</b> May be implemented as macro (evaluates stream multiple times).<br><b>fgetc:</b> Always a function. Safer but possibly slower.
What does feof do?	Returns <b>non-zero</b> if end-of-file indicator is set. Check AFTER a read fails, not before.<br><pre><code>while (fgets(buf, sizeof buf, fp)) { ... }
if (feof(fp)) { /* normal end */ }</code></pre>
What does ferror do?	Returns <b>non-zero</b> if error indicator is set for the stream.<br><pre><code>if (ferror(fp)) { /* I/O error occurred */ }</code></pre>

# === SECTION 14: String Handling ===
What does strcpy do and why is it dangerous?	<b>Copies string</b> including null terminator. <b>Dangerous:</b> No bounds checking, can overflow destination.<br><pre><code>char dest[10];
strcpy(dest, source);  // buffer overflow if source &gt; 9 chars</code></pre>
What does strncpy do?	<b>Copies at most n characters</b>. Warning: May NOT null-terminate if source is too long.<br><pre><code>strncpy(dest, source, sizeof(dest) - 1);
dest[sizeof(dest) - 1] = '\0';  // ensure termination</code></pre>
What does strcmp return?	<b>0</b> if equal, <b>&lt;0</b> if s1 &lt; s2, <b>&gt;0</b> if s1 &gt; s2.<br><pre><code>if (strcmp(s1, s2) == 0) { /* equal */ }</code></pre>
What does strlen return?	<b>Length</b> of string (not including null terminator).<br><pre><code>size_t len = strlen("hello");  // 5</code></pre>
What does strchr do?	Returns pointer to <b>first occurrence</b> of character, or NULL if not found.<br><pre><code>char *p = strchr(str, 'x');</code></pre>
What does strstr do?	Returns pointer to <b>first occurrence</b> of substring, or NULL if not found.<br><pre><code>char *p = strstr(haystack, "needle");</code></pre>
What does strtok do?	<b>Tokenizes</b> a string. Modifies the original string. Uses static state (not thread-safe).<br><pre><code>char *tok = strtok(str, " ,");
while (tok) {
    // process tok
    tok = strtok(NULL, " ,");
}</code></pre>

# === SECTION 15: Type Conversions ===
What are the integer promotions?	Values narrower than int are promoted to <b>int</b> (or unsigned int) in expressions.<br>char, short, bit-fields all promote to int before arithmetic.
What is the usual arithmetic conversion?	When operands have different types, they are converted to a <b>common type</b>:<br>1. If either is long double, convert both<br>2. Else if either is double, convert both<br>3. Else if either is float, convert both<br>4. Else apply integer promotions, then convert to wider/unsigned as needed
What is implicit conversion?	<b>Automatic</b> type conversion by compiler. May lose precision.<br><pre><code>int i = 3.7;     // i = 3 (truncation)
float f = 10/3;  // f = 3.0 (integer division)</code></pre>
What is explicit conversion (casting)?	<b>Programmer-specified</b> type conversion using cast operator.<br><pre><code>double d = (double)10 / 3;  // 3.333...
int *p = (int *)malloc(40);</code></pre>

# === SECTION 16: Undefined Behavior Examples ===
What is undefined behavior (UB)?	Code for which the C standard <b>imposes no requirements</b>. Anything can happen: crash, wrong result, appear to work.
List common causes of undefined behavior.	<pre><code>- Null pointer dereference
- Buffer overflow
- Signed integer overflow
- Use after free
- Double free
- Uninitialized variable use
- Division by zero
- Invalid pointer arithmetic
- Modifying string literals</code></pre>
Why is signed integer overflow undefined?	Allows compilers to <b>optimize</b> assuming it never happens. Two's complement wraparound is NOT guaranteed.<br><pre><code>int x = INT_MAX;
x + 1;  // UB, not guaranteed to wrap</code></pre>
