# C99 (ISO/IEC 9899:1999) Flashcard Deck
# Import: Anki > File > Import, select TSV, Fields separated by Tab
# Enable "Allow HTML in fields"
# Covers all C99 additions compared to C90/C95

# === SECTION 1: Overview and Version Detection ===
What is C99?	<b>ISO/IEC 9899:1999</b> - Major revision of C adding many features: VLAs, inline, restrict, long long, designated initializers, // comments, and more.
What value is __STDC_VERSION__ for C99?	<b>199901L</b><br><pre><code>#if __STDC_VERSION__ &gt;= 199901L
    // C99 or later
#endif</code></pre>
How many new keywords did C99 add?	<b>5 keywords:</b> inline, restrict, _Bool, _Complex, _Imaginary
How many new headers did C99 add?	<b>6 headers:</b> &lt;stdbool.h&gt;, &lt;stdint.h&gt;, &lt;inttypes.h&gt;, &lt;complex.h&gt;, &lt;tgmath.h&gt;, &lt;fenv.h&gt;
How do you request C99 mode in GCC/Clang?	<pre><code>gcc -std=c99 program.c
clang -std=c99 program.c</code></pre>

# === SECTION 2: New Keywords ===
What does the inline keyword do in C99?	<b>Hints</b> to compiler that function calls should be expanded inline. Does not guarantee inlining.<br><pre><code>inline int square(int x) {
    return x * x;
}</code></pre>
What are the inline semantics in C99?	<b>inline alone</b> provides no external definition (for headers).<br><b>extern inline</b> provides external definition.<br><pre><code>// header: inline int f(int x) { return x*2; }
// one .c file: extern inline int f(int x);</code></pre>
What does the restrict keyword do in C99?	<b>Pointer qualifier</b> promising no aliasing. Enables better optimization.<br><pre><code>void copy(int *restrict dest,
          const int *restrict src, size_t n);</code></pre>
When should you use restrict?	When pointers <b>don't alias</b> (point to overlapping memory). If they do alias and you use restrict, behavior is <b>undefined</b>.
What is _Bool in C99?	<b>Boolean type</b> that can hold 0 or 1. Any non-zero value converted to _Bool becomes 1.<br><pre><code>_Bool flag = 42;  // flag = 1</code></pre>
What is _Complex in C99?	<b>Complex number types:</b><br><pre><code>float _Complex
double _Complex
long double _Complex</code></pre><br>Requires &lt;complex.h&gt; for operations.
What is _Imaginary in C99?	<b>Imaginary-only types</b>. Optional feature, rarely supported.<br><pre><code>float _Imaginary
double _Imaginary</code></pre><br>Check __STDC_IEC_559_COMPLEX__ for support.

# === SECTION 3: New Headers ===
What does &lt;stdbool.h&gt; provide?	<b>Boolean macros:</b><br><pre><code>bool   // macro for _Bool
true   // macro for 1
false  // macro for 0
__bool_true_false_are_defined // 1</code></pre>
What does &lt;stdint.h&gt; provide?	<b>Fixed-width integer types:</b><br><pre><code>int8_t, int16_t, int32_t, int64_t
uint8_t, uint16_t, uint32_t, uint64_t
int_least8_t, int_fast8_t, etc.
intmax_t, uintmax_t
intptr_t, uintptr_t</code></pre>
What are the exact-width types in &lt;stdint.h&gt;?	<b>intN_t / uintN_t</b> - Exactly N bits wide. Optional (may not exist on some platforms).<br><pre><code>int32_t x;   // exactly 32 bits
uint64_t y;  // exactly 64 bits</code></pre>
What are the minimum-width types in &lt;stdint.h&gt;?	<b>int_leastN_t / uint_leastN_t</b> - At least N bits. Always available.<br><pre><code>int_least32_t x;  // at least 32 bits</code></pre>
What are the fastest types in &lt;stdint.h&gt;?	<b>int_fastN_t / uint_fastN_t</b> - Fastest type with at least N bits.<br><pre><code>int_fast32_t x;  // fast, at least 32 bits</code></pre>
What are intptr_t and uintptr_t?	<b>Integer types</b> capable of holding a pointer value. Optional.<br><pre><code>void *p = ...;
intptr_t i = (intptr_t)p;
void *q = (void *)i;</code></pre>
What are intmax_t and uintmax_t?	<b>Maximum-width</b> integer types. Can hold any value of any integer type.<br><pre><code>intmax_t big = INTMAX_MAX;</code></pre>
What does &lt;inttypes.h&gt; provide?	<b>Format macros</b> for &lt;stdint.h&gt; types and wide integer functions.<br><pre><code>printf("%" PRId32 "\n", x);   // print int32_t
printf("%" PRIx64 "\n", y);   // print uint64_t as hex
imaxabs, imaxdiv
strtoimax, strtoumax</code></pre>
What are the PRIxN format macros?	<b>printf format specifiers</b> for stdint.h types:<br><pre><code>PRId8, PRId16, PRId32, PRId64   // signed decimal
PRIu8, PRIu16, PRIu32, PRIu64   // unsigned decimal
PRIx8, PRIx16, PRIx32, PRIx64   // hex
PRIo8, PRIo16, PRIo32, PRIo64   // octal</code></pre>
What are the SCNxN format macros?	<b>scanf format specifiers</b> for stdint.h types:<br><pre><code>SCNd32, SCNu64, SCNx16, etc.
int32_t x;
scanf("%" SCNd32, &amp;x);</code></pre>
What does &lt;complex.h&gt; provide?	<b>Complex number support:</b><br><pre><code>complex        // macro for _Complex
imaginary      // macro for _Imaginary (if available)
I              // imaginary unit
creal, cimag   // extract real/imaginary parts
cabs, carg     // magnitude, argument
conj           // conjugate
cexp, clog, cpow, csqrt
csin, ccos, ctan, etc.</code></pre>
How do you create a complex number in C99?	<pre><code>#include &lt;complex.h&gt;
double complex z = 3.0 + 4.0*I;
double r = creal(z);  // 3.0
double i = cimag(z);  // 4.0
double m = cabs(z);   // 5.0</code></pre>
What does &lt;tgmath.h&gt; provide?	<b>Type-generic math macros</b>. Calls appropriate function based on argument type.<br><pre><code>#include &lt;tgmath.h&gt;
float f = 2.0f;
double d = 2.0;
sin(f);  // calls sinf
sin(d);  // calls sin
sin(z);  // calls csin (complex)</code></pre>
What does &lt;fenv.h&gt; provide?	<b>Floating-point environment control:</b><br><pre><code>fenv_t, fexcept_t       // environment types
fegetenv, fesetenv      // save/restore environment
feclearexcept           // clear exception flags
feraiseexcept           // raise exceptions
