Can you declare in for loop init in C99?	<b>Yes</b>. Variable scope is limited to the loop.<br><pre><code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++) {
    // i only exists in loop
}</code></pre>

# === SECTION 11: New Library Functions ===
What is snprintf in C99?	<b>Bounded sprintf</b>. Writes at most n-1 characters plus null terminator.<br><pre><code>char buf[100];
int len = snprintf(buf, sizeof buf, "%d", value);
// returns total that would be written (may exceed n)</code></pre>
What does snprintf return?	The <b>number of characters that would have been written</b> (excluding null) if buffer were large enough. Compare with n to detect truncation.
What are the va_copy macro in C99?	<b>Copies a va_list</b>. Required before reusing a va_list.<br><pre><code>va_list ap, ap_copy;
va_start(ap, fmt);
va_copy(ap_copy, ap);
// use both independently
va_end(ap_copy);
va_end(ap);</code></pre>
What math functions did C99 add?	<pre><code>// Float/long double variants:
sinf, sinl, cosf, cosl, etc.

// New functions:
cbrt, cbrtf, cbrtl       // cube root
exp2, log2               // base 2
expm1, log1p             // for precision near 0
hypot                    // sqrt(x^2 + y^2)
copysign, signbit        // sign operations
nan, isnan, isinf        // NaN/infinity
fma                      // fused multiply-add
trunc, round, nearbyint  // rounding
remainder, remquo        // remainder
fdim, fmax, fmin         // magnitude ops</code></pre>
What is fma in C99?	<b>Fused Multiply-Add</b>. Computes (x*y)+z with single rounding. More precise.<br><pre><code>double result = fma(x, y, z);</code></pre>
What classification macros did C99 add?	<pre><code>isfinite(x)   // not inf or nan
isinf(x)      // is infinity
isnan(x)      // is NaN
isnormal(x)   // is normal (not zero/subnormal/inf/nan)
signbit(x)    // sign bit set
fpclassify(x) // returns FP_ZERO, FP_NORMAL, etc.</code></pre>

# === SECTION 12: Variadic Macros ===
What are variadic macros in C99?	<b>Macros with variable arguments</b> using ... and __VA_ARGS__.<br><pre><code>#define DEBUG(fmt, ...) \
    printf("DEBUG: " fmt, __VA_ARGS__)</code></pre>
How does __VA_ARGS__ work?	<b>Expands to all variadic arguments</b> passed to the macro.<br><pre><code>#define LOG(...) printf(__VA_ARGS__)
LOG("x=%d y=%d\n", x, y);
// expands to: printf("x=%d y=%d\n", x, y);</code></pre>
What is the trailing comma problem with variadic macros?	If no variadic args provided, trailing comma remains.<br><pre><code>#define DBG(fmt, ...) printf(fmt, __VA_ARGS__)
DBG("hello");  // printf("hello", ); -- syntax error</code></pre><br>Fixed in C23 with __VA_OPT__.

# === SECTION 13: __func__ ===
What is __func__ in C99?	<b>Predefined identifier</b> holding the current function name as a string.<br><pre><code>void foo(void) {
    printf("%s\n", __func__);  // prints "foo"
}</code></pre>
How is __func__ implemented?	As if:<br><pre><code>static const char __func__[] = "function-name";</code></pre><br>Exists at function scope, not preprocessor.
What is the difference between __func__ and __FUNCTION__?	<b>__func__:</b> Standard C99<br><b>__FUNCTION__:</b> Non-standard GCC extension (predates C99, but widely supported)

# === SECTION 14: Hexadecimal Floating-Point ===
What are hexadecimal floating-point literals?	<b>Exact representation</b> of binary floating-point values.<br><pre><code>0x1.0p0    // 1.0
0x1.8p1    // 3.0 (1.5 * 2^1)
0x1.FFFp10 // 2047.9375</code></pre>
What is the format of hex float literals?	<b>0x</b> + hex mantissa + <b>p</b> + decimal exponent<br><pre><code>0x[digits].[digits]p[+/-]exponent
// mantissa is hex, exponent is decimal (power of 2)</code></pre>
What printf format prints hex floats?	<b>%a</b> or <b>%A</b><br><pre><code>printf("%a\n", 1.0);  // 0x1p+0
printf("%A\n", 3.5);  // 0X1.CP+1</code></pre>

# === SECTION 15: Boolean Type ===
How do you use bool in C99?	<pre><code>#include &lt;stdbool.h&gt;
bool flag = true;
if (flag) { ... }
flag = false;</code></pre>
What is the relationship between bool and _Bool?	<b>bool</b> is a macro for <b>_Bool</b> defined in &lt;stdbool.h&gt;.<br><b>_Bool</b> is the actual type keyword.
What happens when converting to _Bool?	<b>0 becomes 0</b>, any <b>non-zero becomes 1</b>.<br><pre><code>_Bool b = 42;  // b = 1
_Bool c = 0.5; // c = 1
_Bool d = 0.0; // d = 0</code></pre>

# === SECTION 16: Other C99 Features ===
What is the __STDC_HOSTED__ macro?	<b>1</b> for hosted implementation (full library).<br><b>0</b> for freestanding (minimal, e.g., embedded).
What is __STDC_IEC_559__?	Defined as <b>1</b> if implementation conforms to <b>IEC 60559</b> (IEEE 754) floating-point arithmetic.
What is __STDC_IEC_559_COMPLEX__?	Defined as <b>1</b> if implementation conforms to <b>IEC 60559</b> complex arithmetic.
What is the restrict-qualified array parameter syntax?	<pre><code>void f(int n, int arr[restrict n]);
// Parameter is restrict-qualified pointer to n ints
// Equivalent to: int *restrict arr</code></pre>
What is the static keyword in array parameters?	Guarantees minimum array size to enable optimization.<br><pre><code>void f(int arr[static 10]);
// Caller must provide at least 10 elements
// Enables optimizer to assume arr != NULL</code></pre>
What did C99 change about implicit int?	<b>Removed</b>. Functions must have explicit return type. "Implicit int" was allowed in C89.<br><pre><code>// C89 OK, C99 error:
main() { return 0; }
// C99 requires:
int main(void) { return 0; }</code></pre>
What did C99 change about implicit function declarations?	<b>Removed</b>. Calling undeclared function is constraint violation in C99 (was allowed in C89 assuming int return).
What is the idiv specification in C99?	<b>Truncation toward zero</b>. In C89, integer division direction was implementation-defined for negative operands.<br><pre><code>-7 / 2 = -3  // C99 guarantees this
-7 % 2 = -1  // remainder has sign of dividend</code></pre>
What is universal character names in C99?	<b>Unicode escapes</b> in identifiers and strings.<br><pre><code>\uXXXX   // 4 hex digits (BMP)
\UXXXXXXXX // 8 hex digits (full Unicode)

int caf\u00E9 = 1;  // identifier with e</code></pre>
What is the empty macro argument feature?	C99 allows <b>empty arguments</b> to macros.<br><pre><code>#define FOO(a, b) a ## b
FOO(x, )   // expands to: x</code></pre>
What is #pragma STDC?	Standard pragmas for floating-point control:<br><pre><code>#pragma STDC FENV_ACCESS ON
#pragma STDC FP_CONTRACT OFF
#pragma STDC CX_LIMITED_RANGE ON</code></pre>
"}
